<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1903-10-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1903-10-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="98" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d98">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Conger</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1903-10-09"><hi rend="italic">October 9,
                                1903</hi>.</date></dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 718.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            dispatch No. 1372, of August 21 last, inclosing a copy of a note
                            received by the dean of the diplomatic corps from Prince Ch’ing,
                            advising that thenceforth foreign merchants will not be permitted to buy
                            property in Peking for dwellings or to establish places of business in
                            that city.</p>
                        <p>The Department approves your course in not making any reply to the note
                            at present, but leaving the matter open for such future discussion as
                            events may require.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>